ad me ex Aegypto litteras misit ε after Pharsalus Cicero retired to Brundisium, waited there in uncertainty as to Caesar's intentions towards himself (November, B.C. 48, to September, 13.c. 47); about June he received from him a letter which did not satisfy him (exigue scripta ad Att. xi. 16), but in August another (satis liberales, ad Fam. xiv. 23, letter to his wife) to which he probably here refers ;- and in September, when Caesar lauded, he waited on him and was well received.
